# Problem

## Short

- no tree shaking on `getInitialProps`
- no tree shaking, post terser, on unused imports

## Complete

1. We use [getInitialProps](https://nextjs.org/docs/api-reference/data-fetching/getInitialProps), and thus do not participate in next's [DCE process](https://next-code-elimination.vercel.app/s/MwVo1ERGq), but we desire to.
    - `getServerSide` props provides similar functionality, but we do _not want_ to use our server after first SSR. `getInitialProps` lets us SSR, then transition to a fully client-side app after first-render. For this reason, we believe that `getInitialProps` should continue to be treated like a first-class citizen, versus being recommended against in the next docs.
1. Unused, side-effect free imports are not tree shaken in client builds

**Desired target state**:

```jsx
// pages/_app.js
export { default } from '../libs/app-page/index.js';

// libs/app-page/index.js
import { foo } from "./bar";
// ^ Full import should be tree-shaken or DCE'd from the client side bundle,
// but this module is bundled instead.

function MyApp() {
  return <App />
}

if (typeof window === "undefined") {
  MyApp.getInitialProps = () => {
    foo();
    return {};
  };
}

export default MyApp;
```

Instead, webpack + terser strip the `if () ...` statement only, leaving the import, yielding something equivalent to:

```js
import { foo } from "./bar"; // still here :|
function MyApp() {
  return <App />
}
export default MyApp;
```

# Demonstration

- [this next-code-elimination URL](https://next-code-elimination.vercel.app/s/Wp-xJQSy_)
- [MVP demo](https://github.com/cdaringe/next-weak-shaking)
- [MVP demo on sideEffects: false](https://github.com/cdaringe/next-weak-shaking-side-effects)

# Discussion

- [Terser won't drop the module](https://github.com/terser/terser/issues/168#issuecomment-440362137)
- `sideEffects: "false"` in our next.js root doesn't have an impact in dropping the `'./bar'` module shown above (or the modules in the demos)

For max performance per ENV, we have various uses of code deploying `typeof window === 'undefined'` conditionals. Sometimes, we swap implementations with server vs browser implementations. Other times, we extend a control flow or just execute a side effect for that environment. In both cases, we expect those conditionals to be erased in opposing envs, and they are! When we started our project ~2 years ago, initial tests showed these DCE/erasures successful, and we believed that the associated imports were erased as well. We've recently realized "hey, a lot of this code we thought should have been shaken, turns out is in the browser bundle".

We'd like to discuss what we can do to allow for shaking/erasure of pure imports.

Outside of `getInitialProps`, sometimes we have valid use cases as well to access server only resources in react code:


```js
import cache from 'some/async-localstorage-cache';
const IS_SERVER = typeof window === 'undefined'

function Component() {
  const apiClient = IS_SERVER ? cache.client : createBrowserClient();
  return <MyApiContext client={client} />;
}
```

We could just _create_ the resource again, but that's wasteful, and we care about micro and macro optimizations. This is just a single example after all :)

