I encountered this issue even during local development. When I override NextJS webpack config and add file-loader (v6.2.0), static assets referred in CSS files stop working. As soon as I remove file-loader, static assets in CSS files get loaded correctly.

### Expected Behavior

Adding file-loader to next config shouldn't break images referred from CSS files

### To Reproduce

For example: If contents of my `next.config.js` are:
```js
module.exports = {
  reactStrictMode: true,
  webpack: (config, { buildId, dev, isServer, defaultLoaders, webpack }) => {
    config.module.rules.push({
      test: /\.(jpe?g|png|gif|ico|webp|svg)$/,
      use: [
        {
          loader: 'file-loader',
        },
      ],
    });

    return config
  },
}
```
and my `global.css` file refers a static asset from `public/` directory:
```css
/* styles/global.css */
/* imported in pages/_app.js */

ul {
  list-style: url('../public/img.png');
}
```

then I get a broken image on my site. When I remove the file-loader override, it works fine. Also, JS image imports are working fine in both the cases.

I checked the `.next` folder. WIth file-loader, there are two png files generated for my image:
* `.next/static/[longhash].png`. This file is the actual image.
* `.next/static/media/[filename].[shorthash].png`. This file is corrupt as it doesn't contain the image. When I open it in a plain text editor, I found that it contains JS: `export default __webpack_public_path__ + "[longhash].png";`. A `png` file shouldn't contain any JS code

`.next/static/chunks/pages/_app.js` refers to `.next/static/media/[filename].[shorthash].png` which results in a corrupted image being loaded on the browser.
